Homs and al-Hassaka, which were the urban centers with the highest percentages of divorce, also featured among the most liberal urban areas in Syria. In contrast, Dara’a had the highest percentage of marriages preceding conversion, and yet it had the lowest divorce percentage. Thus, the women’s attitudes towards marriage and divorce in Dara’a demonstrated a more traditional vision of a marriage that couples endure for life, and the role of divorce in self-actualization and self-liberation was traditionally neglected.

Viewed through the lens of gender, this research can contribute to existing theories and offer new insights and questions to answer. The data gathered in this study reveals that religious variables are associated with women’s attitudes toward marriage and divorce in various ways, including the social capital model and the theory of masculine trajectory.[9] Islamic theology illustrates the role of religious factors in women’s autonomy. Moreover, the impact of religion on women’s life domains is a common field of research focusing on religious marriage (Marriage for Islam article), divorce and custody. Yet, this research provides new insights into the role of Islam and imams’ responses to feminism and gender issues.
